Keeping true to Tech2C's ideal of keeping the X axis set up as light as possible, I experimented with using balsa wood and also integrating different elements that went into the whole X carriage set up to minimise parts and screw counts. -The Con of this design is that it becomes harder to swap out the hot ends if need be.
-Silicon sock for the hot end is also a must, as the placement of the BL touch is very close. I highly recommend protecting your BL touch with some Kapton tape and cork sheet.

description.text:
This is a 7 day Pill Organizer with removable containers so you can take your days prescriptions with you.

I found that the Lids got in the way when it came time to refill all the containers. So, I put some flats on the hinge, and added a spring that would apply pressure to hold the lid shut, or open in a vertical position to make it easier to refill the compartments.

I included AM and PM lids, with and without the days of the week on them. I prefer the Pill Containers without the days of the week on them so I can put any container in any position on the 7 day tray. But, several people have expressed a desire to have the days of the week on the lids.

Printer:

MonoPrice Select Mini V1 w/long printbed

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

0.200 mm

Infill:

30%

Notes:

Print 7x Springs, 7x AM Lids and 7x PM Lids OR Print one of each of the AM/PM Lids with the day of the week on it.

It's recommended not to change the orientation of any of the parts. Tolerances are tight, and if your printer prints the X axis a little longer than the Y, or vice versa, the lids won't fit the container, or the containers won't fit in the tray. However, if you must change the tray orientation, please also change everything else to the same orientation to avoid any issues.

The 7 day Tray, the springs, and the Pill Containers don't need supports.

I printed the Lids with supports, and had better luck with removal of the supports without messing up the flats on the hinges when I printed the lids at 0.100mm layer height.

Tools Required: X-acto or Olfa Knife or Small Boxcutter, 2000 grit Sandpaper, Chainsaw, Baseball and Glove.

Before dropping the springs down the slot under the Lid Hinges, I highly recommend polishing the end of the spring that presses against the Lid Hinges because otherwise the lid won't open and close smoothly. I used some 2000 grit wet/dry sandpaper.

Thoroughly clean your chainsaw. This is a much neglected maintenance that will extend the life of your chainsaw considerably. Do not use it on any of your printed parts.

To install the hinges on the container, start with the PM side. With the PM lid vertical to the container, compress the spring, and put one hinge point into the container hinge cup opposite the hinge cup with the crescent cutout in the side of it, and the other side should slide right into the other cup. The small crescent cutout will make it easier to slide the point into the cup.

Install the AM side the same way.

Go outside and play catch with your son (or have imaginary tea with your daughter). Again, often neglected, but will extend your expiry date considerably.

When trying to make the lids click shut when pressed closed, I had better luck scraping the inside of the container opening with a sharp Olfa knife (9mm snap off blade knife) held perpendicular to the plastic, rather than trying to trim the lip of the lid to fit. Trimming the lid almost never worked well for me.
Designed in Fusion 360 as a replacement for one that met an unfortunate demise due to proximity to a campfire. RIP old pill container.

title: MakerFarm Pegasus Single Bowden Mount with IR Sensor

description.text:
After a few revamps and switcheroos, I've finally made a design worthy of printing. This is based on the Prometheus E3D V6 mount, crossed with the mounting plate for the Pegasus 12.

The tabs on the sides of each of the clamp parts are there to attach a Differential IR Sensor such that it sits 1.7mm above the nozzle, which is the recommended height for the sensor. It SHOULD provide you with something in the area of -0.25 to -0.55mm Z-Offset depending on your build surface (solid, like tape or clear, like glass.) If you do use a glass bed on your Pegasus, you will either need to use black paper between the heated bed and glass, or color all of the white parts of the heated bed with a black sharpie. The white parts are too reflective, and your nozzle will definitely crash into the bed on auto leveling.

Special thanks to Colin from MakerFarm for providing the original mounting plate STL files for the Pegasus 12, and Prometheus 3D for the design of the original carriage mount, HERE.

In the redesign, I also adjusted the fan duct length so it would properly hit the printed part, rather than the heat block.

Printer:

MakerFarm Pegasus 12"

Rafts:

No

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

0.200-0.300

Infill:

20%-100% depending on rigidity

Notes:

Printed in PETG for added strength over PLA. Your mileage may vary on infill and resolution... I chose 20% because it was strong enough, but light enough to function without flexing. My first print of the base plate had 100% infill for the first 6mm, and that part alone was heavier than the entire printed mass of the finished product at 20%.

Supports were only needed for the IR sensor tabs, and in the top mounting holes on the back plate for the countersunk screws to rest in.
This was designed in TinkerCad using mockups of the 50mm Blower Fan, 30mm Fan, IR sensor and V6 hotend. The final design was repaired in Meshmixer.

The LEDs are meant to be held in with hot glue, which will double as a diffuser in addition to functioning as an adhesive. As this design does not yet include a charging port or clearly-decided power source yet, it is intended to be held together by its dovetailed shape and rubber bands.

title: Knife Sharpening Guide | Arca Acuta
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text: Arca Acuta (Latin for "Sharp Box"), is a device designed to make knife sharpening with stones easier. Using this device, you can hold your knife perpendicular to a table to sharpen. This is much easier than positioning your blade at a precise angle from a sharpening stone that is placed flat on a table. Be sure to read the instructions in the section headed, "How Do I Use it?" I hope this is as useful to you as it was to me.

Printer:

Flashforge Creator Pro

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Infill:

10%
No post-processing is required. Keep in mind that it may be slightly difficult to take off and put on the lid the first few times you do it.

What Should I Print?

There are two versions of Arca Acuta: a portable version and a version that can be bolted to a workbench. If you want the portable version, print these three files:

  • base.stl
  • lid.stl
  • stoneSupportPlane.stl
If you want the workbench version, print the files:
  • alternateBase.stl
  • stoneSupportPlane.stl

How Do I Use It?

Refer to the images in the gallery for visual aids detailing how this device is to be used. You will need:

  • The 3D printed parts of the version you are using,
  • Any sharpening stones (rectangular prism stones work best),
  • And a rubber band, although this is not always necessary.
The following are the steps to using Arca Acuta:
  1. Place the device on a flat, level surface.
  2. Decide the angle to which you will sharpen your knife's edge, and place the stone-positioning plane in the corresponding slot on the base. Keep in mind that the angles on the base indicate the angle of the entire double beveled knife edge that would result from sharpening (the total angle), so using the slot labeled "20°" actually sharpens each side of your blade to ten degrees. Kitchen knives are typically sharpened to twenty degrees on each side, for a total angle of forty degrees.
  3. Rest your sharpening stone flush against the stone-positioning plane. You can stop it from sliding by strapping a rubber band around the bottom of your stone and the positioning plane if necessary.
  4. Hold one side of the device steady. The lid can be used to extend a side of the base to give you more room to grip.
  5. Hold your knife perpendicular to the level surface as you drag the blade over the stone with light pressure. Be sure to keep your hand out of the way of the blade.
  6. Count the number of strokes you make with the blade, and periodically check the side of the blade that you are not currently sharpening for a burr.
  7. When there is a burr along the whole opposite side of the blade, flip the device 180 degrees and sharpen the other side of the blade. Use the same number of strokes as you did on the first side.
  8. Repeat these steps until you are satisfied with the sharpness of your blade. Use stones of different grits to gradually get a finer edge.

What Is The Inspiration for This?

Being an amateur knife sharpener, I was frustrated with the poor results I was getting using a whetstone on a flat surface. While I was researching the details of honing a blade to be razor-sharp, I encountered the Spyderco Tri-Angle Sharpmaker. I was impressed with the device, but not the price tag, so I designed a new device based off of the Sharpmaker and made it my own. The Arca Acuta is different from the Sharpmaker in the following ways:

  • The Arca Acuta is much less expensive.
  • The Arca Acuta is designed to work with most sharpening stones.
  • The Arca Acuta is more versatile in the blade edges it can produce.
  • The Arca Acuta assembly can only store its stone-positioning plate, no stones themselves like the Sharpmaker.

remixed_from.title: Raspberry Pi 3, Pi 2, and Model B+ case with VESA mounts and more

description.text:
This is a design to 3d print a Raspberry Pi 3 case.
This IS NOT compatible with any previous versions (Raspberry Pi 2 or older)

  • This case comprises of a top and bottom half connected by screws.
  • Your Raspberry Pi 3 has to be connected to the bottom half by screws.
  • Additional mount holes are present on bottom half if you prefer to attach the whole case to a VESA compliant mount.
  • Case exposes all the major pi ports: power, audio, hdmi, Lan, 4 USB ports, memory card.
  • The GPIO pins are not exposed by default BUT there is a perforated tab here - so if you need GPIO ports too, just pressing down with a flat screwdriver over the dotted tabs.
  • Case supports regular size heat sink.
  • Case does not support fan.
Screws needed:

Four M3 x 6mm sheet metal screws - to attach pi to the case.
Four #4 x 3/4" sheet metal screws Alternative: M3 x 18mm - to attach both cases together.
Four 75mm VESA <---Optional

Credit

Being my first design on Thingiverse, I remixed the outstandingly awesome and detailed design by 0110-M-P at https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:922740.
That design has multiple designs for both pi 2 and pi 3 as well as great documentation.

The only changes I made were to add a raspberry logo vent on top. And also, additional vents on the side.

Future improvements:

Printing

If you use a coarse 3d-printing layout (like I did when I printed this), you would have issues with the leaves of the raspberry pi logo not being complete. (see picture) I will fix this soon.

Screws

The M3 screw size for connecting pi to case is a bitlarger than it should be. I had no issues but I was very careful screwing the pi on since it did feel tight.
The Pi actually requires M2.5 screws but the holes on this design are too big.
This was a design flaw in the original one - may not get to fixing this unless I am printing more cases.

Led lights

The led lights in this case are full covered. This should still shine through the plastic.
But when I 3d printed the bottom half of my case in red, I could see the red led clearly. But could barely see the green. I want to make the leds exposed next time.

Memory slot

It works fine now I think I want to expose more of the memory slot.

VESA mounts

I am thinking of making a design without the VESA mounts.

So essentially, I downloaded the top half of the pi case design from the original project (that file was rpi2-top_netfabb.stl)
Imported that into tinkercad.com (the free online 3d tool).
Using TinkerCad, updated the design to add the updated top vents with new side vents.
Downloaded it back as an stl file.
And uploaded it back here!
The "rpi3-bottom_netfabb.stl" file was unchanged.

title: Tevo Black Widow 15 degree extruder and BL touch mount RIGID

description.text:
This is my version of the 15 degree extruder mount modification.

It bolts onto the X axis mounting plate in 4 places that are easy to get to from behind.

It has an end stop on the RH side so its easy to assemble nice and square.

It also includes a BL touch mount which can be left empty if you don't have one.

I designed this to be as rigid and easy to print as possible and I printed it vertically just like its mounted and have the following settings

5 vertical shells
4 top shells
4 bottom shells
25% infill
0.25 layer height

for mounting hardware I used
4 x M4 socket head cap screws and nuts with washers
2 x standard extruder mount screws
2 x standard BL touch screws and nuts

I highly recommend you move the Y axis all the way forward then unbolt 4 grub screws that hold the Y axis in position to the whole X and Z axis gantry then when loose move the assembly so the table edge is directly above the extruder i.e so you achieve a full Y axis print area of 250mm.

for your firmware you want to set the BL touch offset to
X axis 42
Y axis 15
Z axis -2 (approx)

DO NOT USE THE FOLLOWING SETTINGS UNLESS YOU UNDERSTAND WHAT I MENT ABOVE AND YOU UNDERSTAND WHAT THESE SETTINGS DO!

Max travel and probing

define X_MIN_POS 0

define Y_MIN_POS 0

define Z_MIN_POS 0

define X_MAX_POS 375

define Y_MAX_POS 250

define Z_MAX_POS 250

define LEFT_PROBE_BED_POSITION 60

define RIGHT_PROBE_BED_POSITION 335

define FRONT_PROBE_BED_POSITION 35

define BACK_PROBE_BED_POSITION 225

I hold no responsibility for the use of these settings/parts or advice.

title: Da Vinci 1.0 Pro Drop-in E3D Mount with Cooling Fan

description.text:
Drop-in E3D Mount for modified DavInci Printers.

This will not work with stock printer hardware/firmware, as there is no provision for the sensor board.

Inspired by the design on the Prusa hotend mount, I designed this unit with similar lines.

Print in ABS or similar. PLA is not recommended, due to the proximity to the hot-end.
The pieces do not have to be too strong, so 0.25mm, 2 perimeters, 3 top and bottom layers, with 20% infill, is plenty.

The unit will drop into the existing carriage, and is fixed by two screws.
The rear fan is used to cool the part during printing, and unlike most designs, the duct is routed ingeniously inside the carriage, toward the part being cooled. The air stream has been adjusted so as to limit the cooling of the hot-end, but a silicon sock is recommended.

Use Part C for a 40mm radial fan, or Part C2 for a 30mm axial fan.
Unless your printer is good at bridging, use simple supports when printing these parts.

If you intend to use a sensor mount (for auto bed levelling, etc), the carriage will need two holes drilling to accommodate.

I have included the original cad design. Please ensure you credit me in any remixes.

If you like my work, please consider a small donation.

description.text:
Size

Thing size is 77 x 40 x 10 mm3.

Summary

This is a modified version of the fan duct proposed by Oliver_D. The main modification is

  • The air flow is now following Bezier based shapes in the hope that it will facilitate air flow.
  • Output is now single sided in the hope that air speed on the object will be faster, facilitating cooling.

For the rest it is a copy of the original by Oliver_D.

  • A small improvement in the upper-front hole which is made wider as the screw is always difficult to insert (the issue is that the fan screw hole is not perfectly aligned with the radiator blade - slightly bending the blade facilitates the insertion of the screw).
  • Observation: the two long screws go in the bottom of the fan (in case you forget to note when you unmount).
  • How to use it ? See the original explanation from Oliver_D.

Test

  • See the three 3DBenshy's (little boats). Left is with the unmodified RF100. Middle is with the original circular fan duct. Right is with this modified fan duct. It significantly improves the lower half of 3DBenchy (overhang), the bottom of 3DBenchy (now readable) and it slightly improves to top surfaces (more flat). This is still far from perfect, but this is what I can get now from this affordable printer with PLA.

To be improved

  • A small chamfer should be added to facilitate the fitting of this fan duct at the bottom of the radiator
  • Angle may be changed to blow very slightly lower as it looks like the noodle temperature has difficulties to stabilise (I print the raft at 205 now but it dips down to 190 for a period of time before going back up)

description.text:
This micropipette is designed for serious measuring, and fits universal 1 ml pipette tips. You could read the scale on the syringe, or use pure water and a microbalance for farther adjustment. It has an original designed eject button.

Chinese manual

Demonstration

https://youtu.be/qquyA_rF-24

Components

To assemble this, you need following components apart from the printed parts:

  1. a 3 ml plastic syringe with luer taper(screw locker)
  2. a rubber band, Φ=16 mm or about, size #8 or #9 will work.
  3. a silicone or rubber tube, outside 6 mm × inside 4 mm × 5 mm

Assembling

To assemble this, you still need something could drill holes at the plastic syringe, and some normal white glue. As the figs:

  1. Assemble the gears. The groove of the bottom part should be screwed to horizontal.
  2. Install the rubber band. It will exactly fits the groove.
  3. Take the syringe plunger off and drill 4 holes at the handle. Fix it to the previous parts at the rubber band.
  4. Fix the previous parts with the outer case, then install the syringe tube.
  5. Assemble the last 2 parts and the silicone tube, then searing the lure taper with some white glue. Assemble the last parts into the lure taper to complete the pipette.

Printing tips

  1. Designed for no support printing.
  2. There are many threaded parts in this design, please make sure your machine could deal with threads easily.
  3. The part 9 and part 10 may needs different size compensation in your slicer software than others, for fit to standard products preciously.
  4. You may want to print the part 9 first and check if it fits pipette tips perfectly.

Another

  1. For the tested product, all white parts are printed with PLA, and red parts are printed with PETG.
  2. I'm going to make a module for 200 μl tips with a 1 ml syringe, later.
  3. This design have considered to use a spring as the elastic source; I have yet to get a spring to test, though.

title: Chipe - E - Spinner Devotee Remixed
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
VIDEO at the bottom of the page : )

My two daughters (Clara 9 years old, Eva 5 years old) and me are so glade and proud to introduce you our remix.

When I showed them the contest at the beginning of June, they immediately proposed to add to Chip -E- the ability of playing with a hand spinner :)

Two questions was remaining : how and.... how

You have to know that we've been learning Arduino since September 2016 and bought/built our first 3D printer on march this year.

It is our first contest and it was a really fun and exciting experience.

A last thing, we are french, we will try to give you the maximum of information concerning our creation, if something is not clear, please let us know.

Printer:

Geeetech i3 pro B

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.2mm

Infill:

17%

The beginning

We started by printing the original Chip -E-.
We immediately got two difficulties:

  • We don't have the electronic and metal parts from the original kit.
  • How to make the spinner turn.

So we thought through these two problems and made a lot of drawings. As I often say to my children : "the work start always with a pen and a sheet".

We wanted to carry over the maximum of the original Robot even if we had to have hard work on CAD.

That's like this that we got the design of the legs and the arms which are the mains modifications.

The final design needed to print the parts, try them, define modifications, print a new time, try a new time....

After, some hours were spared on the program design with Arduino IDE. We had the basic skills required to build a program, so it was not so hard.

Requirements - part 1

To build our robot, you'll need first to print the 3D models.
Pay attention to print the "belt" two time.
The belt lets tie the base with the midsection and the midsection with the head without any screw.
In this manner, you will be able to assemble and disassemble the robot easily.

Requirements - part 2

You will need some sensors and electronic parts too.

Please find the list:

  • 1x UNO R3 board
  • 1x Prototype Shield
  • 1x L239(D) IC for the DC motors
  • 3x DC motor
  • 2x Wheels
  • 1x PIR sensor
  • 1x Avoiding sensor (IR)
  • 1x LED Matrix
  • 2x Servomotor
  • 1x ON/OFF switch
  • 1x 9V battery
  • 3x ball bearing
  • Some screws, slef-tapping screws, nuts, washers...
  • Some Dupont cables
  • Glue
  • Basic skill in soldering :)
    Most of these parts are available with Arduino starter kits. I don't think that one thing is hard to get (even soldering skill.... :-| )
Step 1 - from the shoes to the base

Assemble the wheels with the DC motors.
Screw the Motors to the legs (Length >32mm)
Stick the shoes with the legs
Screw the legs to the base
Put the belt on the base
Stick the PIR

Step 2 - the midsection

You must start by preparing the prototype shield:
Solder the L239(D) and add pins to get more +5V and GND available.
The L239(D) need 9V so I add pin to get +9V from the battery.
Your prototype shield is ready!!!!

Assemble the UNO R3 board an the prototype shield and put them in the midsection.
Screw the two servomotors (I add glue on their sides).

Assemble the midsection and the base.
Pay attention that all the connectors from the base must come in the midsection (we will see how to connect after)
Put the second belt on the midsection

Step 3 - the arms

Assemble the avoiding sensor with the left arm (no need to screw or stick it).
Assemble the DC motor with the left arm (no need to screw or stick it too).
Stick on each arm, the white thing that I am not able to give it a name :(
Assemble the ball bearings to the hand spinner.

Step 4 - the arms with the body

We need to determine the good positions of each servomotors before proceeding to the assembly.

Considering the right servomotor (seen from the robot).
Open your Arduino IDE, connect the motor to +5V/GND/pin 9 as usually. Starting from the program "Knob", try different angles. Normally, you will determine that the motor has to be set from 50° to 130° to reach the two extremes positions.

After, send 50° to the servomotors and screw the arms.

servomotor at 50° servomotor at 130°

Considering the left arm, seen from the robot.

If you perform the same work, you will determine that the arm is at its lower position when the servomotor is set to 130° and at its upper position when the servomotor is set to 50°.

Screw the arm.

Step 5 - the head

We have chosen to implement a LED Matrix for the eye instead of a liquid crystal display. It's a really funny way to let the robot communicate especially with children.

We have modified the back side of the head to implement an ON/OFF switch.

Stick the LED Matrix display
Screw the ON/OFF switch

Step 6 - connections

Now it's time for the connections.

You'll have to work thoroughly during this step to be sure that the right cables are connected to the right pins.

We've done a scheme explaining the connections:

Step 7 - code

Sources:
As we have taken electronic components from an Elegoo Arduino Starter Kit, we also have taken the examples codes coming for its supplier to build our own code.

So our code is a mix of Arduino examples, Elegoo examples, our knowledge.

The file is in the ZIP.

Upload it to your UNO R3 board.

You are ready to play!!!!!!: )

Improvments

There is a lot to do to go beyond our design!

As you can see, the PIR is not used finally. This components is to sensible and always on HIGH state. That's why we have decided to disconnect it. We could consider other sensors.

We have 3 digital pins free and as many as analog pins. So we can imagine to add Bluetooth ou WIFI control... to add some leds or other sensors for more fun.....

title: Sled mount for precision dial indicator

description.text:
Like? :-D
If this thing made your day better, please click the Like button above. Thank you!
Feel free to PM me if you have any feedback or questions. -CK

==============================================
Description:
This holder is designed to slide a low-force plunger dial indicator smoothly along parallel printer rails. Specifically, the sled is designed to fit 2x 8mm rails, spaced 70mm apart - like in my Flashforge Creator Pro.

Tool:
Shars dial indicator (SKU 303-3111B),with 1" (0.001" graduations). $13 on their website! I can vouch for this being accurate to the thousandth - I checked every 0.100" between 0.000" and 1.000" with NIST-traceable precision gauge blocks :-)

Printing:
Orientation is shown above. This is a trick to get precision features out of a non-precise manufacturing method. Here's why:

Bead stack-up on locating features. Laying the model flat causes a "stepped" effect on the low locating triangles, causing the dial's cylindrical body to catch and not orient vertically. When printing, standing the body up on end allowing beads to lay along the hypotenuse of those lower triangles, i.e. "with the grain", allowing the dial indicator to seat naturally.
tl;dr Turns stairs into ramps.

In this orientation, the sled is designed to be printed at any layer height, 0.10mm to 0.30mm.

Leveling Directions:

  1. Do a "rough level" of your print bed using your favorite method, I use a 0.1mm feeler gauge under the nozzle over each adjustment screw
  2. Center the dial over the back Left or Right screw
  3. Bring the bed up until the dial read 0.100" (well inside the accuracy range).
  4. Make your printer rigid! "Enable steppers" to lock the bed in place.
  5. Gently, with a light touch, slide across to the other screw and measure the difference in height
  6. Pick one height (either extreme, or the average) and adjust both screws to that height
  7. Move to the middle, and slide the sled forward to the front screw. Bring that screw to the chosen height
  8. Remove the dial indicator and sled from the machine
  9. Print your favorite level test - I use my 3 square print:
    https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1776032

That's it - good luck! :-)

description.text: Foldarap Extruder with 608zz bearing

This blaster is unique with its only 1 inch diameter PT, but also with its 12 inch draw and stroke. Why I call it the Liason I have no idea. (Note that the name is different from the actual word Liaison, and is actually pronounced differently.)

Just like the Cherub and Javelin, print the STEP, not the STL.

This took over 8 hours to design, and after 4 hours, I was only doing finishing touches. So the design has gotta be darn near perfect by now.

I estimate that this blaster will get over 300 fps without a SCAR barrel.

9176T5 - 2 ft. : Plunger tube (PT)

9056K92 - 6 in. : Pusher tube (any 1/2" OD aluminum tube with an ID greater than 3/8" will do, but if the walls are too thin, you may need a wire across the mouth or something else to keep the dart from sliding into the tube)

90380A158 - 1 pack: Screws for charging handles - enough for 25 Liasons

92295A106 - 1 pack: Screws for barrel clamp, enough to make 2-4 Liasons depending on how many screws you use per clamp

9637K25 - 1 pack: Main spring, ends need to be closed, enough to make 2 Liasons, 2.5 in bulk.

92325A309 - 1 pack: Plunger screw, holds the plunger head to the plunger rod (the plunger head still needs to be glued or solvent welded together). Enough for 50 Liasons.

1284N166 - 1 pack: O-ring. Enough for 5 Liasons. I use soft Viton because of the lubricants I choose, but if you use regular silicone grease you can go much cheaper.

8975K577: Aluminum reinforcement bar. You can use steel of the same dimensions if you want, and you can also use two 3 foot pieces instead of one 6 foot piece.

8741K36: Delrin square rod for the plunger rod. This stuff can be brittle, so be a little generous on the pilot hole size for the plunger screw.

Non-McMaster parts:

Pine 1 by 1 lumber (actual 3/4" by 3/4") for the barrel support. You could also modify the STEP file and sleeve a 5/8" OD metal tube around the barrel instead.

1/8" steel wire or rod for the catch rods and trigger rods.

17/32" OD and 9/16" OD K&S precision brass tube - the perfect barrel with a very consistent dart fit and relatively low-friction surface. You'll need abut 3 feet (cut down to 32") if you're not using a SCAR barrel on the end, 2 feet if you are.

Optional .125-.1875" ID brass sleeve for the lower catch rod, acts as a bearing and makes trigger action much smoother.

Zipties. Lots of them. These are what hold the shell together. Max width 1/4", max thickness 1/8".

Mag spring- I'm going to use the spring from a PakD that I ruined, I really don't know where to source springs from.

This is a new front for the Commodore Amiga A1011 floppy drive. It allows you to mount 2 slim line floppy drives like the NEC FD 3238T or TEAC FD005. Matching mounting brackets are included, too.

Additionally you need a bit of electronics to supply the floppy drive id's to the Amiga. You can find my solution on github at https://github.com/sgust/Amiga-A1012-PCB. Alternativly you can build the usual Amiga floppy drive id circuit on a piece of prototyping board. It is possible to desolder the special flat foil cable connectors on the floppy drives and replace them with a directly soldered 1mm pitch flat cable which can be connected through a 24 pin 2 row connector to the original cable.

Mounting brackets

The mounting brackets have to be printed with support.

Front

I have split up the front into 3 parts to make it possible to print without support. You have to glue them together after printing. For my print I used the "Desert Tan" filament from https://www.faberdashery.co.uk/products-page/print-materials/desert-tan/, the color matches the rest of the case very well.

Git repository

You can see the history of this files at https://github.com/sgust/Amiga-A1012-front.

license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
I designed this for my anet a6 prusa i3 3d printer. Every time I was printing I needed a flashlight to see in detail what the printer was doing. At first I wanted to add lights to the frame but since the extruder is moving there was never a perfect spot without shadow. So I measured the aluminum extruder base and made a 3d model of it. Then designed something so it would fit the led plate I had. I think I found the same Led in the link below but I am not sure. For the costs it is worth trying. And if not you have to change the clamping part in acad yourself to make it fit to the different measurements of the new led plate. The file is made for a led plate of 47X20 mm.

The power leads are put together with the rest of the extruder cables and go to a switch. Power is taken from the powersupply. The led plate will consume just minimal power so no worries if the powersupply can feed the led's.

Depending on the quality of your print it may or may not be necessary to drill out the holes a bit to make them fit snug over the allan screws. And also check if the ridges in the plate holder arms need some adjustment or not.

I use the led plate holder for a year or so and am still very happy with the result. Because of the slim design you keep a clear view on the printing area and it is lighted very well seen from the front of the printer and side angles of the printer. Seen from the back of the printer a little less ofcourse but to me that is not important because opperation is done from the front.

Many thanks to Gael Langevin, the creator of the InMoov 3D-printed robot (http://www.inmoov.fr).
There are multiple ways to realize 3d vision. Besides the kinect sensor, one could use the Orbbec Astra, which is much smaller, or binocular vision due to 2 cameras in the eyes. Anyway, there should be the possibility to replace the Kinect sensor on the lower chest of the InMoov robot.
The criteria's for this design are: 1. complete removement the kinect and any signs of it, 2. no changes to the torso, 3. same attachment as for the original parts, 4. big parts, easy to print, 5. as much space as possible below the shell.
To attach these parts to the torso, first remove the support at the backside of the left and right parts. Then, screw the left and right parts to the middle. Now the complete thing can be screwed to the torso.

Have fun!
